1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,616
Security teams already have more telemetry in Splunk than they can reasonably investigate by hand.

2
00:00:06,616 --> 00:00:14,225
An analyst still has to search, pivot, correlate events across indexes, and decide which detections are missing.

3
00:00:14,225 --> 00:00:20,978
MirrorLens turns that workflow into an autonomous AI investigation through Splunk's MCP Server.

4
00:00:20,978 --> 00:00:23,097
Here is the product running.

5
00:00:23,097 --> 00:00:28,233
MirrorLens connects to a Splunk instance through the official MCP Server.

6
00:00:28,233 --> 00:00:36,521
For this public demo, I am loading a sample investigation, so no private token or customer data appears in the video.

7
00:00:36,521 --> 00:00:43,002
Once the investigation starts, the AI runs a ReAct loop: reason, act, observe.

8
00:00:43,002 --> 00:00:53,152
It discovers Splunk server details, indexes, hosts, sourcetypes, saved searches, and relevant fields through MCP calls.

9
00:00:53,152 --> 00:01:01,616
The dashboard keeps the main view focused on analyst outcomes, while the agent trace preserves the MCP proof behind the scenes.

10
00:01:01,616 --> 00:01:07,051
The agent then runs targeted SPL queries and adapts based on what it finds.

11
00:01:07,051 --> 00:01:09,859
It is not following a fixed checklist.

12
00:01:09,859 --> 00:01:18,573
It uses the evidence already collected to decide which query to run next, where visibility is weak, and which attack behaviors matter.

13
00:01:18,573 --> 00:01:24,035
The first result is a MITRE ATT&CK mapped investigation summary.

14
00:01:24,035 --> 00:01:33,804
MirrorLens identifies active exfiltration patterns, credential abuse, SIEM visibility gaps, and risky management-plane access.

15
00:01:33,804 --> 00:01:39,171
These findings are presented as security outcomes, not raw query output.

16
00:01:39,171 --> 00:01:42,133
The most important part is validation.

17
00:01:42,133 --> 00:01:46,372
MirrorLens does not just generate SPL detection rules.

18
00:01:46,372 --> 00:01:51,829
It tests those rules against Splunk data through MCP and reports the match count.

19
00:01:51,829 --> 00:01:59,130
When a rule actually fires, the dashboard raises a full-screen detection alert with the rule, SPL, and sample matches.

20
00:01:59,130 --> 00:02:08,749
The investigation closes with a response playbook: containment, eradication, recovery, and risk-ranked next actions.

21
00:02:08,749 --> 00:02:18,301
Then MirrorLens enters watch mode, polling Splunk for new indexes and sourcetypes so it can trigger another investigation when the environment changes.

22
00:02:18,301 --> 00:02:35,991
In under three minutes, MirrorLens shows how Splunk MCP Server can support a new category of agentic security operations: autonomous discovery, adaptive SPL investigation, validated detections, live proof, and a response plan, all streamed to a real-time analyst dashboard.
